===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|cloth|lang=enm}}, {{term|clath|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|clāþ||cloth, clothes, covering, sail}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*klaiþą||garment}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*gleyt-||to cling to, cleave, stick}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|clath||cloth|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|klaid||dress, garment|lang=frr}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|kleed||cloth, article of clothing|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|kleed||robe, dress|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|kleed||dress, garment|lang=nds}}, German {{term|Kleid||dress, garment|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|klæde||cloth, dress|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|kläde||cloth|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|klæði||cloth, dressing|lang=is}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term/t|ang|clīþan||to adhere, stick}}. Compare {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|ngjit||to stick, attach, glue|lang=sq}}.

